The `nextLine()` and `hasNextLine()` methods are both part of the `Scanner` class in Java, but they serve different purposes:

1. **`nextLine()` Method:**
   - `nextLine()` is used to read the next complete line of input from the scanner.
   - It advances the scanner past the current line and returns the input as a `String`.
   - Example:
     ```java
     Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
     String line = scanner.nextLine();
     ```

2. **`hasNextLine()` Method:**
   - `hasNextLine()` is a boolean method that checks if there is another line of input available to be read.
   - It does not consume the input; it only checks if there is more input.
   - Example:
     ```java
     Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
     if (scanner.hasNextLine()) {
         // There is another line of input
     }
     ```


import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;

public class Solution {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        /* Enter your code here. Read input from STDIN. Print output to STDOUT. Your class should be named Solution. */
        
        
        
    Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
    int line_no=1;
    for(line_no=1; sc.hasNextLine();line_no++){
        String line = sc.nextLine();
        
        System.out.println(line_no+ " "+ line);
        
    }
    sc.close();
    }
}